oks/series/guardian-books-network","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Guardian Books Network","type":"series","description":"<p>The Guardian Books Network brings you a selection of our favourite literary content from around the world. To pitch content, make suggestions or send feedback, email <a href=\"mailto:marta.bausells@theguardian.com\">marta.bausells@theguardian.com</a></p>","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/series/guardian-books-network","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/series/guardian-books-network","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"lifeandstyle/food-and-drink","sectionId":"lifeandstyle","webTitle":"Food & drink","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/food-and-drink","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/food-and-drink","sectionName":"Life and style","references":[]},{"id":"lifeandstyle/lifeandstyle","sectionId":"lifeandstyle","webTitle":"Life and style","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/lifeandstyle","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/lifeandstyle/lifeandstyle","sectionName":"Life and style","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tracking/commissioningdesk/uk-culture","webTitle":"UK Culture","type":"tracking","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tracking/commissioningdesk/uk-culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tracking/commissioningdesk/uk-culture","references":[]},{"id":"tone/recipes","webTitle":"Recipes","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/recipes","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/recipes","references":[]},{"id":"tracking/commissioningdesk/uk-communities-and-social","webTitle":"UK Communities and Social","type":"tracking","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tracking/commissioningdesk/uk-communities-and-social","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tracking/commissioningdesk/uk-communities-and-social","references":[]},{"id":"profile/kate-young","webTitle":"Kate Young","type":"contributor","bio":"<p>Kate Young writes about her literary and culinary exploits on her blog Little Library Café. Follow @bakingfiction on <a href=\"https://twitter.com/bakingfiction\">Twitter</a> and <a href=\"https://instagram.com/bakingfiction/\">Instagram</a></p>","firstName":"kate","lastName":"young","r2ContributorId":"72252","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/profile/kate-young","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/profile/kate-young","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-04-07T15:00:50Z","webTitle":"Better Living Through Criticism by AO Scott review – why we need professional critics","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/apr/07/better-living-through-criticism-by-ao-scott-review","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Sukhdev Sandhu","headline":"Better Living Through Criticism by AO Scott review – why we need professional critics","trailText":"Miserabilists, parasites, thwarted practitioners? In an energetic defence of his profession, Scott argues that good art and good criticism go hand in hand","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>In 2012, the New York Times’s widely admired and genially erudite chief film critic AO Scott went to see <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/the-avengers\"><em>The Avengers</em></a>. He left unimpressed. Not only was the movie full of “overblown, skull-assaulting action sequences”, he wrote in his review, but its dirty secret was that it was “a snappy little dialogue comedy dressed up as something else, that something else being a giant ATM for <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/marvel\">Marvel</a> and its new studio overlords, the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/walt-disney-company\">Walt Disney Company</a>”. Egged on by one of its stars, Samuel L Jackson, ranks of fanboys and trolls took to the internet to rain down abuse on Scott for being a pompous egghead who wasn’t down with the people. Their orchestrated outrage even made the news in Brazil and Japan.</p> <p>In the era of media downsizing their numbers have been reduced, but professional critics are still a minority it’s OK to hate. Tolerated and quoted as long as their opinions chime with those of their readers, more often they are abominated as miserable sods and nabobs of negativity; parasites and vampires who feast on the living; thwarted or second-rate creators who take out their disappointment on successful artists. Real people, it’s suggested, are happy just to enjoy art; critics, by contrast, are too sceptical or suspicious. They’re likened to butchers, forensic scientists, prosecutors.</p> <p>Scott argues this is a silly segregation. Everyone thinks about why some films or books or pieces of music work or don’t work. Everyone makes value judgments about art. To deny or seek to downgrade the importance of interpretation and individual responses has, he believes, serious aesthetic and political implications. It “lulls us into passivity”. It “encourages us toward either the defensive group identity of fanhood or a shallow, half-ironic eclecticism”. The dangers of the latter, and it’s hard not to imagine he has one eye on the ongoing freakshow of American politics, is that “we are conscripted into a polarised climate of ideological belligerence in which bluster too often substitutes for argument”.</p> <p>According to Scott, to believe that criticism and art are mutually antagonistic is also a mistake. With his endearing fondness for familial metaphors, he claims criticism is “art’s late-born twin. They draw strength and identity from a single source, even if, like most siblings, their mutual dependency is frequently cloaked in rivalry and suspicion”. He points to individuals who excelled at both: <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/charles-baudelaire\">Baudelaire</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/bernardshaw\">Shaw</a>, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/ts-eliot\">TS Eliot</a>, Berlioz, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/jeanlucgodard\">Godard</a>.</p>  <aside class=\"element element-pullquote element--supporting\"> <blockquote> <p>Criticism, far from being a minor, petty, secondary art, is in fact larger than the others</p> <footer> <cite>AO Scott</cite> </footer> </blockquote> </aside>  <p>His bolder argument is that “all art is successful criticism”. By this he means that all artists find themselves reckoning with the past, judging its achievements, assessing its relevance for the present, revolting against or carrying the baton for it. Huge swaths of contemporary culture – from hip-hop, to the films of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/film/quentintarantino\">Quentin Tarantino</a> and the Coen brothers – are constructed from “borrowing, quotation, and meta-commentary, much of it bracingly original”. Seen in this way, they are not just poster children for postmodernism, but direct descendants of Shakespeare who “ransacked the cupboards of high and low literature, history and folklore in search of viable scenarios, cobbling together scraps of Ovid, Holinshed, Latin comedy, commedia dell’arte sketches”.</p> <p>At times like these, or when he asserts “criticism, far from being a minor, petty, secondary art, is in fact larger than the others”, Scott comes on like <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/music/kanyewest\">Kanye West</a> at his most grandiloquent. The sections of the book styled as dialogues – in which conflicting versions of the author tussle with each other – read clunkily. But if there is nothing here as amusing as David Lee Roth’s quip – “Most music critics love Elvis Costello, because most music critics look like Elvis Costello” – Scott is still an amiable guide through some of the key historical, philosophical and practical issues concerning criticism. Kant makes an appearance, Rilke too, but so does Anton Ego, the restaurant critic from the Pixar animation <em>Ratatouille</em>. A warning about “the promiscuous hurling of adjectives” is worth heeding.</p> <p>Scott writes for a well-regarded broadsheet that prides itself on its extensive arts coverage, can afford to employ fact checkers and abjures the boosterish zeal of zines and passion-project blogs. It would have been interesting, though, to learn how critics occupying a less liberal or centrist position conceive of their jobs. They function – sometimes valuably – as champions for emergent genres or entire art forms, zealots whose ripped‑and-torn prose can expose the ossification of the cultural mainstream.</p> <p>Critics – paid critics, at least – are a dying breed. What price nuance or ambiguity, when the onus is to provoke social-media mayhem, ignite below-the-line indignation and drive online traffic? Qualified enthusiasm doesn’t really cut it against clickbaiting, monetisation-friendly, five-star panegyrics for <em>Avengers</em> sequels. Small wonder that laid-off or freelance writers are migrating to academia: there, sometimes, they can get properly paid. But they pay a price, too, mutating from critics to scholars, from writing for the general public to specialist readers. In the process, something special, some vision of the commons, is fatally eroded.</p> <p>• To order <em>Better Living Through Criticism</em> for £10.39 (RRP £12.99) go to <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalogsearch/result/?q=better+living+through+ciriticsm&amp;order=relevance&amp;dir=desc?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\">bookshop.theguardian.com</a> or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4t46m","wordcount":"868","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/9726d8bb80b5faa3f25ff0c517d26abc693b9eee/0_75_3504_2105/500.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-05-21T11:15:00Z","standfirst