nited behind David Mitchell’s novel Ghostwritten, while the individual judges ruled in favour of Philip Gourevitch’s We Wish to Inform You That Tomorrow We Will be Killed with our Families.<br /></p> <p>Gourevitch’s account of the Rwandan genocide “transcended reportage”, as judge Amanda Foreman said, “haunting all of our thoughts long after we had read it”. It set a standard for books of moral as well as literary stature. Nevertheless, there’s a bit of me that has always mourned the absence of Mitchell from a roll of honour that has grown in stature as the winners have moved through their careers. It’s extraordinary today to think of Zadie Smith as a nervous 25-year-old waiting to step into the limelight of her very first literary award in 2000, or of Chris Ware struggling for words in 2001 as he became the first graphic novelist to win a generalist literary award, not just in the UK but anywhere.<br /></p> <aside class=\"element element-rich-link element--thumbnail\"> <p> <span>Related: </span><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/apr/07/guardian-first-book-award-all-the-winners\">Guardian first book award: all the winners</a> </p> </aside>  <p>But prizes grow up, and find themselves jostling for space in territories where they were once pioneers. This year’s Baileys women’s prize for fiction has no fewer than <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/mar/08/baileys-prize-longlists-self-published-debut-and-10-other-first-novels\">11 first novels on a shortlist of 20</a>, and there has been a proliferation of newer initiatives that reach across genres for exciting new literary departures: think of the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/11/novel-about-john-lennon-and-primal-screaming-wins-goldsmiths-prize\">Goldsmiths prize</a> or the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/mar/27/kate-tempest-ted-hughes-poetry-prize\">Ted Hughes award</a>.<br /></p> <p>So, not without a few tears on the books desk for an institution that has been a centrepiece of our year for nearly two decades, we’ve decided to call it a day.<br /></p> <p>We like to think we’ve played a part in kickstarting the careers of 17 fabulously innovative and diverse authors, ranging from nature writer <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2003/may/11/guardianfirstbookaward2003.guardianfirstbookaward\">Robert Macfarlane</a> to novelist and short story writer <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2006/jan/07/featuresreviews.guardianreview15\">Yiyun Li </a>and back-to-front biographer <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/apr/02/featuresreviews.guardianreview7\">Alexander Masters.</a><br /></p> <p>We’re immensely grateful to the judges who have given their time and expertise over the years, to the Waterstones reading groups who have enlivened the process – and the annual award parties – with their smart, and often pithy, opinions. And to our online books community for their sometimes game-changing <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/jul/31/guardian-first-book-award-10th-finalist\">10th title nominations</a>.<br /></p> <p>So there’s much to celebrate and, rather than sign off in maudlin mood, here are some favourite behind-the-scenes moments. If you have been involved in any part of the prize, please add your own in the comments below.<br /></p> <h2>2001</h2> <p>Comedian and yet-to-be bestselling children’s author Charlie Higson’s passionate championship of Chris Ware’s <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2001/jul/21/biography.highereducation\">Jimmy Corrigan: the Smartest Kid on Earth</a>, which converted even the deeply sceptical science historian Roy Porter into a born again graphic novel fan.</p> <h2>2002</h2> <p>Biographer Hermione Lee coaxing Irvine Welsh into line when he threatened a walkout over the decision to award a British prize to an American: Jonathan Safran Foer for <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2002/jun/08/featuresreviews.guardianreview28\">Everything Is Illuminated</a>. (Also Lisa Jardine’s whispered confidence that she wished the novel had been eligible for the Booker, which she was chairing that year.)</p> <h2>2008</h2> <p>An overheard encounter with Radiohead’s Colin Greenwood at the afterparty for Alex Ross’s <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/mar/14/rest-is-noise-alex-ross\">The Rest Is Noise</a>: </p> <blockquote class=\"quoted\"> <p>“Are you a musician?” </p> <p>“I play a bit in the garage with my brother.”</p> </blockquote> <h2>2009</h2> <p>Petina Gappah’s winner’s speech for <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/apr/19/short-stories-elegy-easterly-gappah\">An Elegy for Easterly</a>: “Did you read the books on the shortlist? I mean, seriously good. If I’d been judging the prize I certainly would not have chosen me.”</p> <h2>2011</h2> <p>Newbie publisher Stefan Tobler’s response to the shortlisting of one of his first titles, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2012/may/29/guardian-first-book-award-2012\">Down the Rabbit Hole,</a> which was nominated by readers: “We launched the year <a href=\"http://www.guardian.co.uk/business/2011/may/20/hmv-sells-waterstones-russian-billionaire\">Waterstones almost went bust</a> and pretty much stopped ordering books for a while. The fact that the <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/guardianfirstbookaward\">Guardian first book award</a> led to Down the Rabbit Hole becoming an overnight success was pure magic.” </p> <h2>2012 </h2> <p>William Dalrymple and Jeanette Winterson being told to behave when they blocked against the award of a single prize, on the grounds that it was impossible to judge fiction against nonfiction. They duly behaved and awarded the prize to Kevin Powers’s novel <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/aug/31/the-yellow-birds-kevin-powers-review\">The Yellow Birds</a> (Katherine Boo’s account of a Mumbai slum, <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/jun/29/behind-beautiful-forevers-katherine-boo-review\">Beyond the Beautiful Forevers</a>, was the underrunner.) </p> <h2>2015</h2> <p>Andrew McMillan’s bracingly literal demonstration that there’s nothing precious about new poetry, at the party to announce his win with<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2015/nov/25/guardian-first-book-award-2015-andrew-mcmillan-poet\"> Physical</a>. The first poet to make it to the podium entertained the crowd by reading from a poem entitled Urination, which began “I’m scared of bumping someone while they piss” - and went on to illustrate why.<br /></p>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4t6jf","wordcount":"822","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/6538c19b704471f5bd9a600f760031a8f3b3df31/0_274_5616_3370/500.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-04-13T23:00:00Z","standfirst":"<p>After 17 years of hunting the best new writing, of terrific winners and terrific rows, we’re saying goodbye to the prize. It will leave lots of great memories – please share yours</p><ul><li><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/apr/07/guardian-first-book-award-all-the-winners\">All the winners of the Guardian first book award, year by year</a></li></ul>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksblog/2016/apr/07/saying-goodbye-to-the-guardian-first-book-award","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksblog/2016/apr/07/saying-goodbye-to-the-guardian-first-book-award","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"6538c19b704471f5bd9a600f760031a8f3b3df31","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/6538c19b704471f5bd9a600f760031a8f3b3df31/0_274_5616_3370/2000.jpg","typeData":{"mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/6538c19b704471f5bd9a600f760031a8f3b3df31","altText":"Andrew McMillan reads a poem at the 2015 ceremony from Physical, the first poetry book to win the prize. Claire Armitstead helps with the sound.","caption":"Andrew McMillan reads a poem at the 2015 ceremony from Physical, the first poetry book to win the prize. Clair