.com/books/kingsleyamis","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/kingsleyamis","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tracking/commissioningdesk/observer-new-review","webTitle":"Observer New Review","type":"tracking","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tracking/commissioningdesk/observer-new-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tracking/commissioningdesk/observer-new-review","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"id":"childrens-books-site/2016/apr/07/how-hard-can-love-be-holly-bourne-review","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"type":"article","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webTitle":"How Hard Can Love Be by Holly Bourne - review","webPublicationDate":"2016-04-07T11:00:22Z","fields":{"wordcount":"441","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4hnfd","standfirst":"<p>‘Holly’s got a really unique writing style that’s both hilarious and serious’</p>","body":"<p>I’m a huge Holly Bourne fan. I first picked up The Manifesto Of How To Be Interesting whilst I was on holiday, and pretty much finished it in one sitting. Am I Normal Yet was the most true to life story with an OCD-suffering main character I’ve read, well, ever – and then this one came along and I was desperate to read it. Helpful tip for you: if you’re desperate to read a book, probably don’t order it online – it might be cheaper but is it worth the wait?</p> <p>Amber’s jetting off to California for the summer, to spend time with the mother who left her, remarried and moved to California, changing her personality at the same time. What’s she to do when all she wants is a little bit of love? Especially when Prom King Kyle arrives, the guy all the girls are after. Is he seriously after Amber? And if so, should she follow Evie’s advice and take it carefully, or should she listen to Lottie, “mount him and worry about it later”. Nobody can deny it: love is hard.</p> <p>After being completely blown away by Holly’s past novels, I expected nothing less from this novel, and I wasn’t disappointed.</p>  <figure class=\"element element-image element--thumbnail\" data-media-id=\"3dc79c58e4e0f6d49773897db191f5ed916d8afc\"> <img src=\"http://media.guim.co.uk/3dc79c58e4e0f6d49773897db191f5ed916d8afc/0_0_313_475/313.jpg\" alt=\"How Hard Can Love Be cover\" width=\"313\" height=\"475\" class=\"gu-image\" /> <figcaption> <span class=\"element-image__caption\"></span> </figcaption> </figure>  <p>Holly’s got a really unique writing style that’s both hilarious and serious, one that knows when to be serious but also can lighten up, which is perfect for this book. It’s one you can read and laugh about, but you can also expect some really serious themes about family troubles, relationships and feminism from.</p> <p>I was also really impressed by how Evie’s story (Am I Normal Yet?) ties in with this new novel; Evie’s presence is clearly baked into this story but not so much that it’s just a byproduct of the first novel.</p> <p>Amber and Kyle are both really well described characters as well. We know so much about the two of them, as well as all the other characters, and the book is written in a realistic and accurate manner. I loved seeing how these two seemingly incompatible characters’ stories intertwined with each others, and it really made this book.</p> <p>I definitely recommend it to anyone looking for their next book to read. Holly’s an amazing writer, and she’s only gone and done it again with How Hard Can Love Be?</p> <p>Plus, she’s got at something too with that question; love’s complicated.</p> <blockquote> <p><strong>• Buy this book at the <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/368950/\">Guardian Bookshop</a></strong></p> </blockquote> <h2><strong>Want to tell the world about a book you’ve read? <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/childrens-books/2011/mar/02/how-do-i-get-involved-guardian-childrens-books\">Join the site</a> and send us your review!</strong></h2>","productionOffice":"UK","trailText":"<strong>confessionsofabooklover:</strong> ‘Holly’s got a really unique writing style that’s both hilarious and serious’","headline":"How Hard Can Love Be by Holly Bourne - review","byline":"confessionsofabooklover"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/2016/apr/07/how-hard-can-love-be-holly-bourne-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/2016/apr/07/how-hard-can-love-be-holly-bourne-review","sectionName":"Children's books","elements":[{"id":"3dc79c58e4e0f6d49773897db191f5ed916d8afc","relation":"body","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/3dc79c58e4e0f6d49773897db191f5ed916d8afc/0_0_313_475/313.jpg","typeData":{"role":"thumbnail","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/3dc79c58e4e0f6d49773897db191f5ed916d8afc","altText":"How Hard Can Love Be cover","caption":"","source":"PR","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"3dc79c58e4e0f6d49773897db191f5ed916d8afc","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/3dc79c58e4e0f6d49773897db191f5ed916d8afc/0_0_313_475/313.jpg","width":"313","height":"475"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/3dc79c58e4e0f6d49773897db191f5ed916d8afc/0_0_313_475/master/313.jpg","typeData":{"role":"thumbnail","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/3dc79c58e4e0f6d49773897db191f5ed916d8afc","altText":"How Hard Can Love Be cover","caption":"","source":"PR","credit":"Photograph: PR","mediaId":"3dc79c58e4e0f6d49773897db191f5ed916d8afc","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/3dc79c58e4e0f6d49773897db191f5ed916d8afc/0_0_313_475/master/313.jpg","width":"313","height":"475","isMaster":"true"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"}]}],"tags":[{"id":"childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","sectionId":"childrens-books-site","webTitle":"Children's books","type":"blog","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/childrens-books-site/childrens-books-site","sectionName":"Children's books","references":[]},{"id":"books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Children and teenagers","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/booksforchildrenandteenagers","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/books","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Books","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"culture/culture","sectionId":"culture","webTitle":"Culture","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/culture/culture","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/culture/culture","sectionName":"Culture","references":[]},{"id":"books/teen-books","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Teen books","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/teen-books","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/teen-books","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/friendship","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Friendship (children and teens)","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/friendship","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/friendship","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"books/teen-romance","sectionId":"books","webTitle":"Teen romance (childrens and teens)","type":"keyword","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/teen-romance","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/teen-romance","sectionName":"Books","references":[]},{"id":"type/article","webTitle":"Article","type":"type","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/articles","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/type/article","references":[]},{"id":"tone/childrens-user-reviews","webTitle":"Children's user reviews","type":"tone","webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/tone/childrens-user-reviews","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/tone/childrens-user-reviews","references":[]}],"references":[]},{"webPublicationDate":"2016-04-07T11:00:22Z","webTitle":"The Death of an Owl by Paul Torday with Piers Torday review – gothic fantasy meets political satire","sectionId":"books","type":"article","rights":{"syndicatable":"true"},"id":"books/2016/apr/07/death-of-an-owl-by-paul-torday-piers-torday-review","fields":{"commentable":"true","byline":"Chris Bryant","headline":"The Death of an Owl by Paul Torday with Piers Torday review – gothic fantasy meets political satire","trailText":"Finished posthumously by his son Piers, Paul Torday’s tale of British politics and revenge is witty and well crafted but far from true to political life","productionOffice":"UK","body":"<p>Owls have exercised a particular hold on the British psyche, from the Celts and the Romans through to <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/childrens-books-site/gallery/2015/nov/24/winnie-the-pooh-inspired-by-a-real-bear\" title=\"\"><em>Winnie-the-Pooh</em></a> – and Paul and Piers Torday use this to powerful effect in this skittish new novel. It’s an intriguing mix of styles, perhaps because when Paul, the author of <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/feb/24/featuresreviews.guardianreview19\" title=\"\"><em>Salmon Fishing in the Yemen</em></a> who <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2013/dec/19/paul-torday-dies-67\" title=\"\">died in 2013</a>, was too ill to continue the book, his son Piers, a children’s writer, took up the task with panache.</p> <p>The plot hinges on a single event, when a barn owl flies into the windscreen of a car driven down a dark country lane by a Conservative MP, Andrew Landford. Also in the car is Landford’s Oxford friend and somewhat reluctant communications adviser, Charles Fryerne, through whose eyes the story is told. What follows is part witty satire on the state of British politics – with a cast of politicians driven by ambition to the exclusion of all honour and humanity – and part gothic drama in which revenge comes painfully and ineluctably. The sense of impending doom as the novel reaches its apocalyptic climax is especially well crafted.</p> <p>There is a problem, though. It takes a long time to get to the owl – 113 pages – and by that time the reader has settled into a comfortable tale of Charles’s semi-requited love for Landford’s intriguing sculptor girlfriend. Charles is a realistically self-deprecatory narrator. He relishes the fact that “the Fryernes had achieved a kind of obscurity so comprehensive as to be rather unusual in its way”. He is so lacking in self-confidence that, despite his dislike of ostentation, he joins an expensive Bullingdon-style dining club at Oxford just because he has been invited. By his own account, his sole virtue is his inability to tell a lie, and yet for some inexplicable reason he is inveigled into helping the odious Landford achieve his political ambitions. Since he clearly loathes Landford, this leaves you wondering why.</p> <p>There are other plot anomalies. When the Tory leader of the opposition resigns, the loyalist Landford is considered one of just two possible candidates to replace him, despite being so new that he has never served on the government or opposition frontbench – something that has never happened in Britain. Similarly unconvincing is the Tory MP (he is meant to be the likable one) who is made to say: “I am very, very important. There’s even talk – although, being you, you either haven’t heard or don’t care – of me becoming a junior minister one of these days.” I have never heard an MP speak like that. Yes, people see MPs – me included – as arrogant and narcissistic, but if a politician were to mouth off like that, he would be slain by the press, by Twitter or by his colleagues in very short order.</p> <p>The least credible plot twist of all is when a newspaper deliberately outs a leading Tory MP as gay. There is, thankfully, no UK newspaper that would do that today. They might tease readers, make indirect allusions and even place a photograph of the MP on the same page as a story about another gay man – but none would be so crass, scurrilous or immoral as to out someone. It’s true that snide wink-wink innuendo used to be the order of the day when it came to matters of sexuality. I recall, for instance, driving <a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/politics/tonyblair\" title=\"\">Tony Blair</a> down to the Christchurch byelection in 1993 and explaining to him why the Lib Dems referred to the Tory candidate, Rob Hayward, as “unmarried”. It worked for the Liberal Democrats in their despicable 1983 campaign in which they presented the byelection as a “straight choice” between Peter Tatchell and Simon Hughes. But no British politician or party today would seek to use an opponent’s sexuality against him or her – if only because it would backfire.</p> <p>This isn’t an attempt at political verisimilitude. It’s a delightful gothic fantasy, infused with an element of taut anger. But one day someone will write a novel that shines a light on modern British politics. It will have credible characters and a believable plot – and it will get the simple diurnal facts about politics right. I live in hope.</p> <p>• Chris Bryant is MP for Rhondda and shadow leader of the House of Commons. To order <a href=\"https://bookshop.theguardian.com/catalog/product/view/id/390104/?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article\" title=\"\"><em>The Death of an Owl</em></a><em> </em>for £11.99 (RRP £14.99) go to bookshop.theguardian.com or call 0330 333 6846. Free UK p&amp;p over £10, online orders only. Phone orders min p&amp;p of £1.99.</p>","shortUrl":"http://gu.com/p/4t32z","wordcount":"790","thumbnail":"http://media.guim.co.uk/b4cd4dca631d0f3050c4d7e888d05d223472654a/0_245_3844_2308/500.jpg","commentCloseDate":"2016-05-21T14:37:00Z","standfirst":"<p>Finished posthumously by his son Piers, Paul Torday’s tale of British politics and revenge is witty and well crafted but far from true to political life</p>"},"webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/books/2016/apr/07/death-of-an-owl-by-paul-torday-piers-torday-review","apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/books/2016/apr/07/death-of-an-owl-by-paul-torday-piers-torday-review","sectionName":"Books","elements":[{"id":"b4cd4dca631d0f3050c4d7e888d05d223472654a","relation":"main","type":"image","assets":[{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/b4cd4dca631d0f3050c4d7e888d05d223472654a/0_245_3844_2308/2000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"(c) David Tipling","picdarUrn":"GD*37423958","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/b4cd4dca631d0f3050c4d7e888d05d223472654a","suppliersReference":"123521470","altText":"A barn owl causes the plot to take flight in the Tordays’ novel","caption":"A barn owl changes the course of events in the Tordays’ novel. Photograph: Getty Images","photographer":"David Tipling","source":"Getty Images","credit":"Photograph: David Tipling/Getty Images","mediaId":"b4cd4dca631d0f3050c4d7e888d05d223472654a","displayCredit":"false","imageType":"Photograph","secureFile":"https://media.guim.co.uk/b4cd4dca631d0f3050c4d7e888d05d223472654a/0_245_3844_2308/2000.jpg","width":"2000","height":"1200"},"mimeType":"image/jpeg"},{"type":"image","file":"http://media.guim.co.uk/b4cd4dca631d0f3050c4d7e888d05d223472654a/0_245_3844_2308/1000.jpg","typeData":{"copyright":"(c) David Tipling","picdarUrn":"GD*37423958","mediaApiUri":"https://api.media.gutools.co.uk/images/b4cd4dca631d0f3050c4d7e888d05d223472654a","suppliersReference":"123521470","altText":"A barn owl causes the plot to take flight in the Tordays’ novel","caption":"A barn owl changes the course of events in the Tordays’ novel. Photograph: Getty Images","photographer":"David Tipling","source":"Getty Images","credit":"